node.text: Dating back to the 19th century, the humble pantry box was a smart invention-it’s the ideal receptacle because it’s made of wood, which breathes; it keeps critters out (unless they chew a hole in the side!); and it blocks sunlight. Things that plastic and glass containers don’t do. No surprise that pantry boxes remain one of the most popular primitive collectibles to this day. #countryhomecollected

node.title: “How to Spot a Fake” Friday, Pantry Boxes

node.text: Ironstone is one of our favorite collectibles. With their simple beauty and creamy white glaze, these timeless pieces are a stable in any country home. Find out what to look for the next time you’re out hunting for ironstone at the flea market. Show us your ironstone collection by tagging #mycountryhome for a chance to be featured! #countryhomecollected

node.title: “How to Spot a Fake” Friday, Ironstone

node.text: We have a soft spot for the mellow, worn-in look of an antique cutting board. Whether used for chopping or just for display, vintage boards add warmth and age to a kitchen. But there are many reproductions out there so be sure to look out for these telltale signs of a true antique board before forking over your cash! #mycountryhome #countryhomecollected #antiquing

node.title: “How to Spot a Fake” Friday, Cutting Boards
